      "callEndedTimestamp": null,
      "isPinned": false,
      "content": "** **\n- **While VOD reviewing, ask yourself the following questions**\n  - What actually went wrong here?\n  - Could I have rotated earlier?\n  - Was that fight worth taking?\n  - Did I not check my surroundings enough?\n  - It’s not about blaming yourself — it’s about being honest and figuring out what you could’ve done differently. That’s how you turn a loss into progress.\n\n- You can also watch how top pros handle those same situations. Maybe they rotated differently or played a fight slower. Comparing your decisions to theirs helps you start thinking like them — and that’s where the real growth happens.\n\n- Improving your game sense isn’t about grinding 10 hours a day. It’s about playing smart, thinking ahead, and letting each match teach you something.\n\n- The more aware you are of your past mistakes, the less likely you are to repeat them — and before you know it, you’ll be playing cleaner, making better calls, and climbing way more consistently.\n\n- Don’t play repetitive scenarios, play on varied fields for varied practice.\n\n- Best way to improve is by playing a lot of tournaments.\n\n- Watch more endgames from youtube videos, etc.\n\n- Pro vod review. Will help you understand how pros are getting better, And win a lot and I mean a lot of money.\n\n- Play more ranked. Playing ranked is going to improve your game sense. You will learn a lot of exploits in tournaments and more.\n\n- Watch pro players. I recommend IGL ones, Like khanada, Acorn, MrSavage and more.",
